    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-10-21T02:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-10-21T02:05:00-05:00" n="331"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                <head>331. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Australia</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d331fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, INCO–WHEAT <gloss target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss>. Confidential;
                        Flash. Passed to the White House and <gloss target="#t_USIA1"
                        >USIA</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Canberra</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-10-21T07:05:00+00:00">October 21, 1966,
                        0705Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2153. Reference: State 69437.<note n="2" xml:id="d331fn2">
                        <ref target="#d330">Document 330</ref>.</note> For Acting Secretary from
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName>. Please inform <persName
                        corresp="#p_SBK1">Brom Smith</persName> immediately. In bilateral discussion
                    between President and <persName corresp="#p_HHE3">Holt</persName> minimum wheat
                    price issue strongly raised with McEwen taking lead.</p>
                <p>Although State 69437 was available, U.S. position and considerations bearing on
                    it were not sufficiently clear for President to make reply which he would like
                    to be able to do tomorrow before leaving Canberra. <pb facs="0836" n="802"
                        xml:id="pg_802"/> Discussion confused because 40-cent increase did not match
                    Australian statement they wished to raise minimum from $1.53 to $1.85; that is,
                    32 cents.</p>
                <p>Therefore please send answers immediately to following questions: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>How would $1.85 minimum affect U.S. agricultural interests, size of
                            U.S. subsidy, etc.?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Australians say U.K. insistence on treating low wheat price as balance
                            of payments respite no longer acceptable. They want our support for
                            higher price. What are U.S. policy considerations bearing on this
                            choice?</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>What precisely are special factors bearing on the Canadian as opposed
                            to Australian position?</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>How far does flexibility in present U.S. position now go? What is
                            upper limit we now think we can accept and still get an
                            agreement?</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>What do you recommend by way of a Presidential response to <persName
                                corresp="#p_HHE3">Holt</persName> tomorrow?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Text of aide-memoire follows.<note n="3" xml:id="d331fn3">Sent in telegram 2155
                        from Canberra, October 21. (Department of State, Central Files, INCO–WHEAT
                            <gloss target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss>) For a supplement to this
                        aide-memoire, see <ref target="#d332">Document 332</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CCM2">
                            <hi rend="strong">Clark</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
